shared_text:
The PTA at Theodore Roosevelt School - Weehawken, NJ
June 4 at 8:58 AM ·

TRS Parents,
The TRSPTA needs you! Three of the four current board members have children in 6th grade, so we can no longer serve on the board of TRSPTA.
If you or someone you know is interested in being on the board please let us know.

If no one volunteers by June 4, 2020, we will sadly be forced to formally end our relationship with the PTA and close our chapter.

Please spread the word & consider volunteering. Without the PTA, there would be no book fair, after-school enrichment, Fun Day, gardening, class trips, dances & socials, DARE reception, Teacher Appreciation, graduation, and many other things! Without parents to volunteer to lead, there will be no PTA.
text:
The PTA at Theodore Roosevelt School - Weehawken, NJ
June 4 at 8:58 AM ·

TRS Parents,
The TRSPTA needs you! Three of the four current board members have children in 6th grade, so we can no longer serve on the board of TRSPTA.
If you or someone you know is interested in being on the board please let us know.

If no one volunteers by June 4, 2020, we will sadly be forced to formally end our relationship with the PTA and close our chapter.

Please spread the word & consider volunteering. Without the PTA, there would be no book fair, after-school enrichment, Fun Day, gardening, class trips, dances & socials, DARE reception, Teacher Appreciation, graduation, and many other things! post_text:
WEEphoto Challenge
April 19 - Day 7
Lighting
Let’s learn a little bit about how to put different kinds of light to work. You can use a lamp, flashlight or different angles in the sunlight. You will need to be aware of where the light is coming from and how that will affect your image.
Front Lighting: This is when the light source is in front of the subject. Front lighting lights up a subject very well, but bright front lighting may cause long shadows behind the subject.
Side Lighting: Side lighting is light that comes from one side of the subject. This type of lighting is often used to add a moody look to a photo because it tends to cast shadows across the front of the subject. Think of it this way: If you take a photograph of a person with the sun to that person’s right side, you’ll often find that the left side of that person’s face is shadow because it isn’t in direct sunlight.
Pick one subject and try two different kinds of lighting. Submit both photos.
Post on Twitter by 7:30PM w your child’s age/grade & #WEEphoto

post_text:
April 18 - Day 6 #WeePhoto Challenge
Close-Ups or Macro Photography
This is a genre of photography that involves extremely close-up shots of objects to make them take up most of the frame. Get really close to what you are going to be photographing today. If at first, your close-ups are blurry, you may be too close to the subject; stand back a bit and try using the zoom. Every lens has a minimum focusing distance. If the subject is closer than this distance, the camera cannot focus the lens. Some of the most popular subjects of macro photography include living organisms such as flowers and insects. However, inanimate objects can also be photographed in this style. Don’t limit yourself to these options, anything can be photographed like this! Make us guess what it is!
Post on Twitter by 7:30PM.
Make sure to include child’s name/grade & #WEEphoto

post_text:
Day 5 of #WEEphoto challenge is here! All ages welcome.
Topic: The Rule of Thirds.

Rule of Thirds
An essential principle of good photography, the Rule of Thirds divides a photo into thirds vertically and/or horizontally and places important features at intersections or along the dividing lines. Place an imaginary grid on top of your image. The grid breaks the image down into 9 parts. The rule of thirds consists in positioning your main subject in one of the four intersections of your imaginary grid, immediately improving your photos by making your compositions more balanced and interesting.
Post your picture on Twitter with grade/age & #WEEphoto by 7:30PM.

#WEEphoto Challenge -open to all students!
April 14 - Day 2
Animal / Pets
Take a picture of an animal (a pet or go find a squirrel, bird or something...maybe a bug?). If you’re safe inside today, a stuffed animal will do! As you photograph it, get an idea of what would make it a good photo. Capturing animals in their natural environment is always amazing, OR try an environment that is definitely NOT natural for a fun twist. Connect with your subject and be aware of the lighting and environment. Think about perspective and placement.

Entries should be posted on Twitter by 7:30pm. Please include your child’s first name and grade and tag #weephoto.

shared_text:
WomenRising
February 28 at 6:39 PM ·

Today is the last day of #TeenDatingViolenceAwarenessMonth, and we were happy to close out this week with Weehawken School District. ⁣
⁣
Margaret Abrams, WR’s Domestic Violence Response Team Coordinator (DVRT), visits Weehawken High School each February to talk to the students about building healthy relationships at a young age and how to recognize potentially abusive relationships in the hopes to avoid domestic violence from forming later in life.⁣
⁣
In exchange, the students donate thousands of diapers to WomenRising’s clients. ⁣

February 28 at 6:39 PM ·

Today is the last day of #TeenDatingViolenceAwarenessMonth, and we were happy to close out this week with Weehawken School District. ⁣

Margaret Abrams, WR’s Domestic Violence Response Team Coordinator (DVRT), visits Weehawken High School each February to talk to the students about building healthy relationships at a young age and how to recognize potentially abusive relationships in the hopes to avoid domestic violence from forming later in life.⁣
⁣
In exchange, the students donate thousands of diapers to WomenRising’s clients. ⁣

post_text:
Congratulations to TRS student, Sadie Thompson, on taking 1st Place in the 5th grade category for the National Archives Youth Art Competition!
The National Archives invited students in grades 4-6 across the nation to participate. All students were asked to create a piece of art that answered one question - what does the 100th anniversary of women winning the right to vote mean to you and your community?
Congrats, Sadie!
#WeeAreProud

post_text: 1/8/2020 - Today there was some plumbing work done at Roosevelt School. As a result, there was an odor. As a precaution, we have moved all Roosevelt Extended Care students to Webster School today. There is no need for panic. Everyone is safe. Students are being transported to DWS via school bus. Please pick up all TRS Extended Care students from DWS today.
